I've had numerous issues with the Paul located on K street but never bothered to leave a review because I do like their food (most of the time). Today I ordered a veggie quinoa salad to-go and after waiting for 10 minutes (it wasn't busy), a different cashier than the one who rang me up realized that a veggie quiche was rang in instead of the salad. I realized that the quiche is more expensive ($10.45) than the salad ($9.95) and also brought this to their attention with which I was met with a look of confusion. When they realized I wanted a refund for the difference, the cashier who rang me up dug in his pocket and handed me the $0.50 difference in change (pennies included!). I asked if I could have it put back on my card and they simply answered "No". I realize that it is only $0.50 but the matter in which it was handled was highly inappropriate and dismissive on account of an employee's mistake! Their customer service has continuously been poor but I've always brushed it off because the food was decent and their location was convenient for work, but I think this was just the last straw for me. Teach your people customer service and refunds should be able to be provided using the original payment method!

The place has low lighting,  bistro atmosphere, bar chairs and tables,  sofa and cushiony chairs, and "wooden" floors.  Upon walking in you are greeted with an array of pastries and smiling faced employees. A breakfast and everything else menu is hung on the walls.  When I was here there was a short line of 4 people.  I ordered the smoked salmon salad and a glass is water (right out the tap), never offered a choice of dressings or even extra napkins as other people within the same line who ordered drinks or was told where to obtain a straw. I was presented with a table number, a tray and 1 silverware.  Waiting for my food to come, the ambient noise of music filled the room as I found a place to sit.  Food arrives shortly after.   The plate was will presented as if The chefs really care about presentation.  The bread was hard as stale bread that's been baked art 6 am and left out in open air.  The salmon was flavorful and the tomatoes actually tasted as if it was garden grown with plenty of sunlight.  Since I had tap water,  I put a cucumber into it,  to balance the pH. I know it is going to take longer than me eating, but it made me feel good.  After pointing out the hard bread,  they were nice enough to warm up a new piece.  I will return one day.

In an era where hipster, local coffee shops dominate the DC scene, it begs the question- is there a place for commercial coffee shops like Paul. After all it's a French style coffee shop/bakery chain. Each shop looks the same. I'd like to make the argument there is a little space for them in the city. Here's why:  1) They offer ample seating and space when the other local coffee shops are too full on a weekend. Paul has a dining room and tables fit for two scattered throughout the shop.  2) They have consistently good pastries including chocolate croissants and macaroons.  3) Their coffee tends to be decent and much cheaper than third wave coffee shops like Philz or La Colombe.  If you need a place to work/think and those local, hipster shops are too full, stop by Paul and grab a cafe au lait and a warm chocolate croissant.
